05314nam a22006975i 9780226642505DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019037138  a9780226642505  a(DE-B1597)549531  a(OCoLC)1158109526  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aB317b.P334 2020 7aPOL0000002bisacsh1 aPangle, Thomas L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSocrates Founding Political Philosophy in Xenophon's "Economist", "Symposium", and "Apology" /cThomas L. Pangle. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Socratic Science of Economics -- t2. The Case for Farming -- t3. Teaching Socrates How a Gentleman Educates His Wife -- t4. Teaching Socrates the Activities of a Gentleman -- t5. Teaching Socrates How a Gentleman Educates His Overseers -- t6. Teaching Socrates the Art of Farming -- t7. Socrates Leading the Festivity of Gentlemen in the Symposium -- t8. Deliberate Defiance in the Apology -- tAppendix: Preliminary Observations on the Contrasts and Complementarities between Xenophon’s and Plato’s Presentations of Socrates -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe oeuvre of the Greek historian Xenophon, whose works stand with those of Plato as essential accounts of the teachings of Socrates, has seen a new surge of attention after decades in the shadows. And no one has done more in recent years to spearhead the revival than Thomas L. Pangle. Here, Pangle provides a sequel to his study of Xenophon’s longest account of Socrates, the Memorabilia, expanding the scope of inquiry through an incisive treatment of Xenophon’s shorter Socratic dialogues, the Economist, the Symposium, and the Apology of Socrates to the Jury. What Pangle reveals is that these three depictions of Socrates complement and, in fact, serve to complete the Memorabilia in meaningful ways. Unlike the Socrates of Plato, Xenophon’s Socrates is more complicated and human, an individual working out the problem of what it means to live well and virtuously. While the Memorabilia defends Socrates by stressing his likeness to conventionally respectable gentlemen, Xenophon’s remaining Socratic texts offer a more nuanced characterization by highlighting how Socrates also diverges from conventions of gentlemanliness in his virtues, behaviors, and peculiar views of "idian life and governmental rule. One question threads through the three writings: Which way of life best promotes human existence, politics, and economics—that of the Socratic political philosopher with his philosophic virtues or that of the gentleman with his familial, civic, and moral virtues? In uncovering the nuances of Xenophon’s approach to the issue in the Economist, Symposium, and Apology, Pangle’s book cements the significance of these writings for the field and their value for shaping a fuller conception of just who Socrates was and what he taught.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSocrates-Political and social views. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aApology.  aCritobulus.  aMemorabilia.  aOeconomicus.  aPlato.  aPolitical Philosophy.  aSocrates.  aSymposium.  aXenophon.  aeconomics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEB